and the synthetic, combining themes of Western sci-fi.

249
00:13:44,199 --> 00:13:46,620
And there's always been a little bit

250
00:13:46,620 --> 00:13:48,861
of a dash of a fantasy element in Borderlands.

251
00:13:49,461 --> 00:13:53,243
I always say to people that Borderlands never really gets old to work on,

252
00:13:53,243 --> 00:13:57,605
because as a sound designer, the world is so very interesting and varied.

253
00:13:57,605 --> 00:14:02,348
It doesn't feel like you're ever doing the same thing at all on a day-to-day basis.

254
00:14:02,348 --> 00:14:05,890
So Wonderlands actually presented us with a new aesthetic challenge

255
00:14:05,890 --> 00:14:08,911
to dive deep into the high fantasy aspect

256
00:14:08,911 --> 00:14:14,334
and really focus on cultivating a Borderlands-y take on magic systems and melee weapons.

257
00:14:14,947 --> 00:14:17,687
There were also some noticeable design changes

258
00:14:17,687 --> 00:14:20,408
that influenced our aesthetic choices.

259
00:14:20,408 --> 00:14:24,149
We had quite a few new systems being added to the game,

260
00:14:24,149 --> 00:14:26,370
in addition to some overhauls of the previous systems

261
00:14:26,370 --> 00:14:27,530
we were working with.

262
00:14:27,530 --> 00:14:30,311
And a lot of these big design overhauls

263
00:14:30,311 --> 00:14:32,612
influenced the aesthetic we were aiming for.

264
00:14:32,612 --> 00:14:35,172
So to amp up the fantasy theme,

265
00:14:35,172 --> 00:14:37,773
we did sort of a remix of the Borderlands 3 weapon system

266
00:14:37,773 --> 00:14:40,154
by adding crossbow barrels and behaviors

267
00:14:40,154 --> 00:14:41,894
to familiar Borderlands franchises

268
00:14:41,894 --> 00:14:43,295
and weapons manufacturers.

269
00:14:45,280 --> 00:14:55,989
Grenades were also replaced by spells, and they have some really cool behaviors, and I'll cover those in a little bit more depth later, because there's a lot to those.

270
00:14:55,989 --> 00:15:01,994
We also deepened our melee mechanics by adding melee weapons as a form of loot in the game.

271
00:15:01,994 --> 00:15:08,580
So the melee weapon system kind of piggybacks on the modular gun system, essentially.

272
00:15:13,020 --> 00:15:15,362
So as Wonderlands was spinning up on pre-production,

273
00:15:15,362 --> 00:15:18,766
we were still in the midst of Borderlands 3 DLC production.

274
00:15:18,766 --> 00:15:21,148
So at the time, we were a bit short on resources

275
00:15:21,148 --> 00:15:24,452
to kind of get the jumpstart on Wonderlands that we needed.

276
00:15:24,452 --> 00:15:27,535
Our associate director of sound design, Brian Fieser,

277
00:15:27,535 --> 00:15:29,457
had worked with Paul Stoughton in the past,

278
00:15:29,457 --> 00:15:32,761
and we contacted him to see if he would

279
00:15:32,761 --> 00:15:34,963
want to do some contract work with us.

280
00:15:35,602 --> 00:15:39,926
Stoughton, I don't know if you know Paul Stoughton, but he is an industry veteran with amazing

281
00:15:39,926 --> 00:15:45,071
talent and a reputation for creating and releasing his own very high quality professional sound

282
00:15:45,071 --> 00:15:47,113
libraries under his company, Penguin Grenade.

283
00:15:48,282 --> 00:15:54,763
We tasked them with helping us basically create our own personal sound libraries

284
00:15:54,763 --> 00:16:00,104
for our team to use once everyone rolled off the DLC and straight into production of Mordorlands.

285
00:16:00,104 --> 00:16:05,586
We requested a highly organic library of raw, processed, and designed content.

286
00:16:05,586 --> 00:16:10,267
Having this content for our designers to work with would help ensure that our designers were

287
00:16:10,267 --> 00:16:14,088
utilizing the same palette of material in their work,

288
00:16:14,088 --> 00:16:17,748
so we could all have a really nice cohesion to our magic audio.

289
00:16:18,869 --> 00:16:25,795
So the raw source material mainly consisted of recordings of organic material that had been cleaned up for us to use and put into SoundMiner.

290
00:16:25,795 --> 00:16:37,244
So in the next slide I'll play various examples of what that raw source material is using a few different elemental types.

291
00:17:43,263 --> 00:17:43,658
Oops.

292
00:17:50,166 --> 00:17:55,089
So once we had that raw source, we would move on and process that source.

293
00:17:55,089 --> 00:17:59,251
So the process source basically takes the raw source that was recorded and

294
00:17:59,251 --> 00:18:00,772
adds some heavier processing to it.

295
00:18:00,772 --> 00:18:06,595
So this stuff was intended to be designed and used as a magic layer for our

296
00:18:06,595 --> 00:18:10,638
designers, but you know, it gave, it basically allows the designers to have a

297
00:18:10,638 --> 00:18:14,320
lot of wiggle room to have their own forms of creative expression with it.

298
00:19:28,473 --> 00:19:29,815
And finally, there's design source.

299
00:19:29,815 --> 00:19:31,996
We didn't do a whole lot of pre-design source

300
00:19:31,996 --> 00:19:34,198
because pretty much all of this work

301
00:19:34,198 --> 00:19:36,160
happened before a lot of the art and design

302
00:19:36,160 --> 00:19:38,021
had been created in the game.

303
00:19:38,021 --> 00:19:41,644
So it was kind of like more audio concept art

304
00:19:41,644 --> 00:19:43,345
is what I kind of think of it as.

305
00:19:43,345 --> 00:19:47,208
Either way, it became pretty useful stuff in the end anyway,

306
00:19:47,208 --> 00:19:50,051
and it really kind of got everyone inspired

307
00:19:50,051 --> 00:19:52,473
in thinking about what the real sound

308
00:19:52,473 --> 00:19:55,855
of Wonderland's magic was gonna be.

309
00:19:55,855 --> 00:19:57,496
So here's some examples of that.

310
00:20:31,454 --> 00:20:34,356
So now that we've covered the aesthetic aspects

311
00:20:34,356 --> 00:20:36,257
of Wonderlands, over the next few slides,

312
00:20:36,257 --> 00:20:38,819
we'll talk about how we expanded our modular systems

313
00:20:38,819 --> 00:20:41,461
from Borderlands 3.

314
00:20:41,461 --> 00:20:43,262
So on Tiny Tina's Wonderlands, we

315
00:20:43,262 --> 00:20:47,485
wanted to take that modularity a step further.

316
00:20:47,485 --> 00:20:49,906
We kept our existing modular system for the guns,

317
00:20:49,906 --> 00:20:52,428
but then we also added modular functionality

318
00:20:52,428 --> 00:20:54,309
to other aspects of the games.

319
00:20:54,309 --> 00:20:58,472
Most notably, that was the spell casting and the melee weapons.

320
00:21:02,714 --> 00:21:08,358
The cool thing about the Borderlands 3 system is when it came to our new magic guns and our crossbow weapons,

321
00:21:08,358 --> 00:21:12,020
we had a system we knew already would mostly just work.

322
00:21:12,020 --> 00:21:17,424
Outside of that, we just had some new RTC PCs that we needed in Wwise,

323
00:21:17,424 --> 00:21:22,447
and after that, the biggest challenge really was nailing down how we wanted the things to sound.

324
00:21:23,388 --> 00:21:26,230
So for the crossbow barrels, we had a challenge.

325
00:21:26,230 --> 00:21:29,852
We wanted them to sound punchy and pretty satisfying

326
00:21:29,852 --> 00:21:31,894
to shoot, kind of like any other Borderlands weapon

327
00:21:31,894 --> 00:21:34,615
in the game, but we needed it to also have this

328
00:21:34,615 --> 00:21:37,317
kind of like old school, kind of medieval crossbow

329
00:21:37,317 --> 00:21:38,078
sounding aesthetic.

330
00:21:39,103 --> 00:21:45,466
It took a decent amount of experimentation with the content, but we figured out if we replaced sounds

331
00:21:45,466 --> 00:21:50,489
from certain parts on the other guns from Borderlands 3, but kept some key choice layers,

332
00:21:50,489 --> 00:21:56,572
we could keep the familiar signature brand identity for our weapons, but also make them feel, you know, fresh and unique.

333
00:21:57,320 --> 00:21:59,961
So yeah, a good example would be the TORG weapons.

334
00:21:59,961 --> 00:22:02,422
We kept some of those mechanical bombastic thumpy sounds

335
00:22:02,422 --> 00:22:06,744
that you would typically notice in a TORG weapon,

336
00:22:06,744 --> 00:22:10,266
but we added some more of that medieval ballista kind of

337
00:22:10,266 --> 00:22:12,307
aspect to the aesthetic of that sound.

338
00:22:12,307 --> 00:22:16,308
So snappy releases, satisfying projectile whooshes,

339
00:22:16,308 --> 00:22:20,110
and here's a video medley of some of those crossbow weapons

340
00:22:20,110 --> 00:22:22,531
to kind of give you an idea of what we ended up going with.

341
00:23:11,452 --> 00:23:13,293
We also had magic weapons in the game.

342
00:23:13,293 --> 00:23:16,095
So for magic weapons, we also removed a lot of those

343
00:23:16,095 --> 00:23:18,176
like native Borderlands 3 layers

344
00:23:18,176 --> 00:23:20,557
and kept some choice layers for supplementation.

345
00:23:20,557 --> 00:23:23,059
So for example, like a doll assault rifle

346
00:23:23,059 --> 00:23:25,800
might keep some of those mechanical Call of Duty

347
00:23:25,800 --> 00:23:28,442
kind of sounding elements and the reload sounds

348
00:23:28,442 --> 00:23:30,423
so they could stay uniquely to doll.

349
00:23:30,423 --> 00:23:33,965
But we added new layers,

350
00:23:33,965 --> 00:23:36,547
it's added to represent like the new magical content.

351
00:23:37,268 --> 00:23:40,693
We kept focus primarily on the weapons elemental magic properties

352
00:23:40,693 --> 00:23:44,398
and crafted those transients and tails around those elements.

353
00:23:44,398 --> 00:23:49,385
We also kept that design language just kind of familiar with those weapon manufacturers.

354
00:23:49,385 --> 00:23:53,331
This next slide will show you some of the cool magic weapons we worked on.

355
00:24:42,312 --> 00:24:44,273
I love those poison reloads so much.

356
00:24:46,534 --> 00:24:49,596
So yeah, melee weapons presented an entirely new challenge,

357
00:24:49,596 --> 00:24:52,698
and we didn't have a system for anything like this yet,

358
00:24:52,698 --> 00:24:55,099
so we kind of got to dreaming up one.

359
00:24:55,099 --> 00:24:57,581
I knew that we would want to continue our philosophy

360
00:24:57,581 --> 00:25:00,062
of adding audio to specific types of parts,

361
00:25:00,062 --> 00:25:02,544
but I wasn't exactly sure how going into it.

